{{Other people|Ali ibn Isa (disambiguation){{!}}Ali ibn Isa}}
'''ʿAlī ibn ʿĪsā al-Asṭurlābī''' ({{lang-ar|علي بن عيسى}}) was an [[Arabs|Arab]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=H.|first1=Suter,|title=al-BADĪʿ al-ASṬURLĀBĪ|url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1163/1573-3912_islam_SIM_0993|website=Encyclopaedia of Islam, Second Edition|publisher=Brill|accessdate=11 February 2017|language=en|doi=10.1163/1573-3912_islam_sim_0993}}</ref> astronomer and [[Islamic geography|geographer]] of the 9th century. He wrote a treatise on the [[astrolabe]] and was an opponent of [[astrology]]. During the reign of [[al-Ma'mun]], and together with [[Khālid ibn ʿAbd al‐Malik al‐Marwarrūdhī]], he participated in an expedition to the Plain of [[Sinjar]] to measure the length of a degree, or the [[circumference of the Earth]].{{sfn|Bolt|2007}} He measured the [[Earth]]'s circumference, getting a result of 40,248&nbsp;km (or, according to other sources, 41,436&nbsp;km).{{Citation needed|date=October 2011}}

