'''Emmanuel de Martonne''' (1 April 1873 – 24 July 1955) was a [[French people|French]] [[geographer]]. He participated in the [[Paris Peace Conference, 1919|Paris Peace Conference]].

==Early life and education==
He was born on 1 April 1873 in [[Chabris]], [[Indre]], France,<ref name="smith">{{cite web|last=Smith|first=Charles H.|title=Martonne, Emmanuel-Louis-Eugène de (France 1873–1955)|url=http://people.wku.edu/charles.smith/chronob/MART1873.htm|accessdate=19 January 2013|year=2005}}</ref> and was the son-in-law of [[Paul Vidal de la Blache]].<ref name="britishacademy">{{cite book|author=British Academy|authorlink=British Academy|title=Biographical Memoirs of Fellows|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DzmWOT_26JEC&pg=PA202|accessdate=2 March 2013|year=2003|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=978-0-19-726302-0|page=202}}</ref> In 1882, he entered the [[École Normale Supérieure]].<ref name="bowd">{{cite web|last=Bowd |first=Gavin |title=Emmanuel de Martonne et la niassance de la grande Roumanie |url=http://www.rjgeo.ro/atasuri/revue%20roumaine_55_2/G.%20Bowd.pdf |format=PDF |publisher=Romanian Journal of Geography |accessdate=5 March 2013 |language=French |date=13 May 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6EwPk3t5Y?url=http://www.rjgeo.ro/atasuri/revue%20roumaine_55_2/G.%20Bowd.pdf |archivedate=2013-03-07 |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref> He graduated three years later with a degree in history and geography.<ref name="smith" /> After that, he worked with [[Ferdinand von Richthofen]] and [[Albrecht Penck]].<ref name="smith" />

==Career==
In 1899, de Martonne became a professor at the [[University of Rennes]].{{sfn|Brock|Giusti|2007|pp=125–144}}
There he founded the institute of geography on the German model.{{sfn|Lorimer|Withers|2012|p=64}}
In October 1905 he moved to the University of Lyon, replaced at Rennes by [[Antoine Vacher]].{{sfn|Lorimer|Withers|2012|p=66}}
Four years later he moved to the [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]].{{sfn|Brock|Giusti|2007|pp=125–144}}
During [[World War I]] (1914–18), in January 1915 the Geographical Commission was established in close liaison with the 2nd Bureau of the Army Staff with six geographers, [[Albert Demangeon]], [[Lucien Gallois]], Emmanuel de Martonne, [[Emmanuel de Margerie]], Louis Raveneau and [[Paul Vidal de La Blache]].{{sfn|Ginsburger|2010|p=293}}

During the [[Paris Peace Conference, 1919|Paris Peace Conference]] after the war, de Martonne was an adviser of [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (France)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]] [[André Tardieu]] and [[Prime Minister (France)|Prime Minister]] [[Georges Clemenceau]].<ref name="palsky">{{cite journal|last=Palsky|first=Gilles|author-link=Gilles Palsky|title=Emmanuel de Martonne and the Ethnographical Cartography of Central Europe (1917–1920)|journal=[[Imago Mundi]]|year=2002|volume=54|issue=1|pages=111–119|doi=10.1080/03085690208592961|url=http://www.gla.ac.uk/0t4/crcees/files/summerschool/readings/school10/reading_list/gilles.pdf|accessdate=19 January 2013|issn=1479-7801|oclc=55939414}}</ref> He also lobbied for the return of [[Alsace-Lorraine]] to the French.<ref name="flint">{{cite book|last=Flint|first=Colin|title=The Geography of War and Peace: From Death Camps to Diplomats|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Za08XQfp3ZwC&pg=PA32|accessdate=5 March 2013|year=2004|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=978-0-19-534751-7|page=32}}</ref> De Martonne was also secretary of the ''Comité D'études'', which worked on fixing boundary issues following the war, especially in [[Romania]] and the [[Balkans]].<ref name="palsky" /><ref name="geocarrefour">{{cite journal|last1=Maccaglia|first1=Fabrizio|last2=Morelle|first2=Marie|title=Pour une géographie du droit: un chantier urbain|journal=Géocarrefour|date=29 November 2012|issn=1627-4873|url=http://geocarrefour.revues.org/8722?lang=en|accessdate=5 March 2013}}</ref> He was familiar with [[Central Europe]] and Romania, as he had conducted studies in the [[Southern Carpathians]] earlier in his life.<ref name="palsky" />

After that, he taught at the [[University of Cluj]] in 1921.<ref name="livezeanu">{{cite book|last=Livezeanu|first=Irina|authorlink=Irina Livezeanu|title=Cultural Politics in Greater Romania: Regionalism, Nation Building & Ethnic Struggle, 1918–1930|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5ysbpAyJjoAC&pg=PA225|accessdate=5 March 2013|year=2000|publisher=[[Cornell University Press]]|isbn=978-0-8014-8688-3|page=225}}</ref> He died on 24 July 1955 in [[Sceaux, Hauts-de-Seine|Sceaux]], a commune near [[Paris]].<ref name="smith"/>

==Awards and honors==
He became an honorary member of the [[Geographical Society of the USSR]] in 1933.,<ref name="sovietencyclopedia">{{cite web|title=Martonne, Emmanuel de|url=http://encyclopedia2.thefreedictionary.com/Emmanuel+de+Martonne|work=[[Great Soviet Encyclopedia]]|publisher=The Free Dictionary|accessdate=19 January 2013}}</ref> and, from 1938 to 1952, was president of the [[International Geographical Union]].<ref name="sovietencyclopedia"/> He was awarded the [[Cullum Geographical Medal]] in 1939, and the [[Victoria Medal (geography)|Victoria Medal]] in 1950.<ref name="smith" /><ref name="ags">{{cite web|title=Timeline of the American Geographical Society|url=http://www.amergeog.org/archives/AGS_timeline1851-2010.pdf|publisher=[[American Geographical Society]]|accessdate=2 March 2013|page=14}}</ref> He became a member of the [[French Academy of Sciences]] in 1942.<ref name="sovietencyclopedia"/>

==Publications==
In 1909, he published the first edition of his book ''Traité de géographie physique: Climat, Hydrographie, Relief du sol, Biogéographie''. It contains 396 [[three-dimensional]], painstakingly researched illustrations and maps. It covers many aspects of geography, including different [[map projection]]s, the [[geographic coordinate system]], [[physical geography]], [[climate]], [[hydrography]], [[erosion]], [[glacier]]s, and [[biogeography]].<ref name="fl">{{cite journal|title=Reviews|journal=[[The Journal of Geology]]|date=May–June 1910|volume=18|issue=4|pages=387–390|jstor=30079349|publisher=[[University of Chicago Press]]|oclc=818922761}}</ref><ref name="johnson">{{cite journal|last=Johnson|first=D. W.|title=Traite de Geographie physique|journal=Bulletin of the American Geographical Society|year=1910|volume=42|issue=7|pages=533–535|jstor=199543|publisher=[[American Geographical Society]]|oclc=225227274|doi=10.2307/199543}}</ref> The second edition was published in 1913, and the third in 1920.{{sfn|Brock|Giusti|2007|pp=125–144}}

He published ''Les Alpes: Géographie générale'', a study about the [[Alps]], in 1926. This led to the "De Martonne aridity index".<ref name="oliver">{{cite book|last=Oliver|first=John E.|title=The Encyclopedia of World Climatology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-mwbAsxpRr0C&pg=PA90|accessdate=5 March 2013|year=2005|publisher=[[Springer Publishing]]|isbn=978-1-4020-3264-6|page=90}}</ref>

