[[File:Burger_OtokKriznaJama.jpg|thumb|right|400px|Subterranean isle in one of the 22 lakes in [[Cross Cave]] in [[Slovenia]]]]
An '''underground lake''' or '''subterranean lake''' is a lake under the surface of the Earth. Such lakes may be associated with [[cave]]s, [[aquifer]]s, or [[spring (hydrosphere)|springs]]. They are typically very low in [[salinity]].

The largest non-[[subglacial lake]] in the world is in [[Dragon's Breath Cave]] in [[Namibia]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lakescientist.com/dragons-breath-cave-holds-worlds-largest-underground-lake/ |title=Dragon’s Breath Cave Holds the World’s Largest Underground Lake |last=Kelly |first=Daniel |date=24 January 2014 |website=Lake Scientist |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150301130831/http://www.lakescientist.com/dragons-breath-cave-holds-worlds-largest-underground-lake/ |archive-date=1 March 2015 |dead-url=no |access-date=31 May 2016 |df= }}</ref> with an area of almost {{convert|2|ha|acre|0|lk=on}},<ref name=NationalGeographic>{{cite web|url=http://www.odyssei.com/travel-tips/6223.html|title=Dragon's Breath, Namibia|publisher=National Geographic |accessdate=28 August 2012}}</ref> and the second largest is in [[Craighead Caverns]] in [[Tennessee]], [[United States]].

